  "prompt": "Why does a helicopter hover, but not move with constant velocity when there is no net force?",
  "response": "Let me explain why a helicopter behaves differently from an ideal object in classical mechanics:\n\n1. Helicopter hovering requires constant energy input\n- The rotor blades must continuously generate lift\n- This requires the engine to work against gravity and maintain rotor rotation\n\n2. Hovering is an active process, not a passive state\n- Unlike objects moving at constant velocity in Newton's first law\n- Requires constant thrust equal to the helicopter's weight\n\n3. Precision control mechanisms are needed\n- Cyclic and collective pitch controls adjust blade angles\n- Constant small adjustments maintain position\n\n4. No natural inertial motion like in space\n- Earth's atmosphere and gravity demand active stabilization\n- Friction and air resistance constantly affect the aircraft\n\n5. Mechanical system with complex dynamics\n- Rotor blade aerodynamics\n- Engine power transmission\n- Center of mass variations\n\nEssentially, hovering is an active, energy-consuming process where the helicopter continuously generates lift to counteract gravitational forces, unlike passive constant-velocity motion described by classical mechanics.\n\nThe helicopter doesn't naturally maintain velocity without input because atmospheric conditions and gravitational effects require continuous mechanical intervention.",
